This is a "street" address (as opposed to postal boxes which are not normally associated to street locations) which is the most common way of specifying a location on a street map. It should eventually be compliant with an ISO standard.

This empty abstract class is the root of the address specification tree. The design strategy is to define "address elements" commonly used across multiple cultures and countries, and to allow any country to define an address type of its own by combinations of these elements. New elements are allowed if they have character string representations. The printed address for any country would be a template of the strings specified in its subtype of address. Note that any viable instance for any subtype of abstract address would also be a viable AD_Address, as long as all of its address elements are defined.
This class is used to represent functions for the calculation of a costs associated to the traversal of the various parts of a network.
A general description of the cost function.
An algebraic formulae describing this cost.
The cost function for complete routes.
This association relates a costed turn to is defining cost function.
The cost function used to calculate the cost for this turn.

Defines a single route instruction or advisory. An instruction can cover multiple maneuvers as in "turn right and then immediately left." Most such examples involve maneuvers that are not separated by "long" liniks.
The cost calculated for this turn, and the following link. For example, the intruction migth say "turn right and go 40km" in which case the value for a distance-based cost function is "40km."
A turn for which the cost has been calculated according to the indicated cost function.
The cost calculated for this turn.

The turn that represents this costed turn with the cost stripped out (or not yet calculated).
The costed turn for this turn for this cost function
Basic navigation request specifying only the source (starting point) and destination (ending point) of the requested route. Cost function used are based on general criteria.

This service interface supplies operation central to navigating and tracking a single target. Capabilities is a function that returns a sequence of route request types that are properly handled by the service supporting this interface.
This operation returns a proposed route matching the criteria pass in through the request.
This association relates a costed link to its geometric version.

A transfer Node is a node in a combined network that is the union of several component junctions. Its links and turns contain all the links and turns of the component junctions plus transfers that move from a link in one component network to a link in one of the other component networks. The combined network can be recast (alternately represented) by a single network in which all component junctions of a single transfer node have been unioned into a single node (of type junction), whose links consist of all the component links and whose turns consist of all the component turns combined with the transfers.
A transfer link is a link in a combined network whose boundary nodes are in different component networks.
A transfer is a turn that occurs at a transfer node and which has entry and exit links connected to separate component junctions

This class is used to list lane restrictions. Lane numbers are counted from the normal outside edge of allowable travel (rightmost in the US the Americas and most of Europe; leftmost in the UK Australia and Japan).
Allowed Lanes are ones from which the turn can be made both legally or physically if the vehicle has a large turning radius). The turning radii if given are ordered in the same manner as the allowed lanes and are the minimum turning radius required of a vehicle making this turn from this lane.
The allowed lanes from which the turn can be made. "+1" is the left most lane. Positive numbers count from the left. "-1" is the right most lane. Negative numbers count from the right.
The disallowed lanes from which the turn cannot be made. "+1" is the left most lane. Positive numbers count from the left. "-1" is the right most lane. Negative numbers count from the right.

This class specifies when a network entity may be traversed. The constraint may be listed in two distinct manner when the network entity is close to traffic or when it is opened. Co-constraints on this entity may further specify vehicles types.
Time when the entity is open for use. If NULL, the value is assumed to be the complement of the "forbiddenTime."
Time when the entity is closed for use. If NULL, the value is assumed to be the complement of the "allowedTime."
This is a constraint on the type or size of a vehicle that is allowed to traverse a link or a turn.
This class is an abstract class whose subtypes specify turn and link restrictions.

The attribute "temporalValidity" specifies the times at which this constraint is valid. In a temproal constraint, the temporalValidity may be used to indicate a larter time frame within which the temporal constaint is valid. For example, the temporalValidity may be "April-September" while the temproal constraint list "Monday-Friday, 8AM to 10AM" meaing that the constaint is active only during those months, those days and between those times.
This is a natural language description of the constraint, and may contain additional advisory information to be used in creatng instructions that this constraint plays a role in.

A temporal restriction limits the applicability ot the target to a particular instant or period of time. If an avoidance target expires, it need no longer be avoided. In a route request, a temporal restriction for a target specifices when that target should be visited. This may make some route request impossible, in which case, the service may return a best approximation, or simply a fail status.

Co-Constraints are sets of contraints that may be linked logically. The meaning of this linkage represents constraints that have multiple criteria, such as "taxi-only from 8AM to 10AM" which is a vehicle and temporal constraint.
This is a mechanism for traversing a route.
This indicates whether this link is navigable in this direction.
This indicates whether this link is navigable in this direction.
This association indicates the potential entry truns into a link. Each turn enters a unique link. Each link can have multiple entry turns.
This association indicates the potential exit turns out of a link. Each turn exits a unique link. Each link can have multiple exit turns.

This class is a list of descriptions of targets for a route that it must either pass through or avoid. The route satisfies the target list if it passes through each location so indicated and avoids each target so indicated. The types of description may vary although most common descriptions are either coordinate positions or street-level addresses.
Whether or not the order of the via point list is part of the route requirements.
Targets are used in route Request to indicate features or positions that must be either traversed or avoided. The link attribute "avoid" determines which.
Whether or not the targets are to be visited or avoided.
This is a representation of a position with respect to a network.

This class is used for routes defined by a geometry (a composite curve) and start and stop positions on that geometry. A route is calculated from and optimizes a cost function from the set of possible routes that traverse a set of target positions. The recalculate function determines a new route that optimizes the new cost function from the passed target position to the end of the route. If the cost function has not changed the new route should coincide with old one.
The two canonical representations of a route are 1) an ordered list of directed links to be traversed and 2) an ordered list of maneuver to be made. Each maneuver advisory or route instruction is associated to either a link, a maneuver or a turn of the route.
Recalculation of a route from some point along it (given by a target). The returned route follows the original at least up to the passed target.
The point along the current route where the returned route can diverge.
The new cost function for the remainder of the route.

A maneuver is a legal sequence of actions, given by a sequence of turns, each of which terminates on the link that is the start of the next turn. Most maneuvers are single turns, but some turn's traversability are dependent on route history (as a ending turn in a U-turn across a divided highway). Since in this case, the turn's traversability cannot be decided by a single link's history, the maneuver extends that history to a sufficient length to determine traversability. The total length of most maneuvers is quite short.

The NT_Turn object represents a mechanism for traversing from one link to another. Each turn will be located at a node of the underlying topology and will form the bridge for a link entering the node and a link exiting the node. The use of turns allows a restricted network (one with constraints) to be represented by an unrestricted one. The use of the word "turn" does not necessarily reflect a change of direction. Going straight through an intersection is one such viable option and would be represented by a "NT_Turn." In public transport such as a rail system the "NT_Turns" are routes through "stations" connecting one incoming "train" with one outgoing "train." NT_Turns are thus called "connections" when speaking of airport and have temporal constraints based on the availability of the "links" that is on flight times.

The exitCount indicates how far around the intersection the exit link occurs relative to entrance link. In right-hand lane systems the count is counter-clockwise. In left-hand lande systems the count is clockwise. In non-road systems, the number can usually be ignored.

This operation populated the Feature association with the features that satisfies this query. Normally, this will reuse this FX_QueryFeatureCollection, but that is dependent on the semantics of the implementation.
The name of a feature collection for use in target lists for navigation requests.
This is the basic class for feature collections.
This Boolean-valued object indicated whether there is any meaning in the order of this collection.
The association that aggregates features into a collection.
The features in this collection. Ther ordering may or may not be of semanitc importance depending on the "ordered" attribute of the feature collection.
This is the basic feature data structure.
The local name, or identity of the feature. This will usually be listed in the Name Space for the Container Feature Collection for this Feature.

A record containing all the attributes of this feature. This mechanism is used to assure that any combination of attributes can be associated to a feature. This will support most type systems semantics normally used for feature representations, including, strong, weak, dynamic, and untyped.
The point ellipse is the same as a point circle except that the error is given by an ellipse defined by the parameters given.

A point circle is a point with an error estimate that is a metric circle of a given radius. It should be noted that this circle is not a circle in the coordinate reference system of the point unless the reference system is a local engineering one.
The point arc is the same as a point circle except that the error is given by an pair of arcs between two given radii and two given bearing angles. .
This class locates a position or place within the network. It should always be interpretable as a direct position (coordinate in a reference system) an address or as a network position.
